  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Solomon's chariots, horses, and riches. - In order to prove by facts the fulfilment of the divine promise which Solomon received in answer to his prayer at Gibeon, we have in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 3:16-28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " a narrative of Solomon's wise judgment, then in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " an account of his public officers; and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 5:1-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the royal magnificence, glory, and wisdom of his reign is further portrayed. In our Chronicle, on the contrary, we have in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 1:14-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " only a short statement as to his chariots and horses, and the wealth in silver and gold to be found in the land, merely for the purpose of showing how God had given him riches and possessions. This statement recurs verbally in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:26-29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the concluding remarks on the riches and splendour of Solomon's reign; while in the parallel passage, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 9:13-28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", it is repeated in an abridged form, and interwoven with other statements. From this we see in how free and peculiar a manner the author of the Chronicle has made use of his authorities, and how he has arranged the material derived from them according to his own special plan.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(Note: The assertion of Thenius on 1 Kings 10:26., that he found this section in his authorities in two different places and in different connections, copied them mechanically, and only towards the end of the second passage remarked the repetition and then abridged the statement, is at once refuted by observing, that in the supposed repetition the first half (2 Chronicles 9:25-26) does not at all agree with 1 Kings 10:26, but coincides with the statement in 1 Kings 5:6-7.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(Note: The assertion of Thenius on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
